SLAPNAP Report:

SLAPNAP Team

24 February, 2020

1 Executive summary

The NAbs studied in this analysis are . There were 4952 sequences extracted from the CATNAP database; 326 sequences had complete data and were used in the analysis. The analysis considered 1 measure of sensitivity: IC-50.

Prediction of each outcome was performed using extreme gradient boosting with tuning parameters selected using a limited grid search and cross-validation.

The specific algorithms used in learning process are described in Table 1.1.

Table 1.1: Algorithms used in the analysis
Label Description
SL.xgboost.2 boosted regression trees with maximum depth of 2
SL.xgboost.4 boosted regression trees with maximum depth of 4
SL.xgboost.6 boosted regression trees with maximum depth of 6
SL.xgboost.8 boosted regression trees with maximum depth of 8

The predictive ability of the learner was assessed using cross-validation. The estimated cross-validated \(R^2\) of the super learner for predicting continuous outcomes are shown in Table 1.2.

Table 1.2: Estimates of 5-fold cross-validated R-squared for super learner predictions of the three continuous-valued outcomes (n = 326 observations with complete sequence data).
CV - R^2 Lower 95% CI Upper 95% CI
IC-50 0.071 -0.038 0.169

We define the marginal population-level importance of a subgroup of features as the difference in population predictiveness between the best possible prediction function based on the features under consideration plus geographic confounders versus only geographic confounders. In Table 1.3, we display the groups of variables and their ranked marginal population variable importance for predicting IC-50. For variable group definitions, please refer to Table 3.1.

Table 1.3: Ranked marginal variable importance of groups relative to the group of geographic confounders predicting IC-50. Importance is measured via \(R^2\). A total of 326 pseudoviruses with complete information were used in this analysis. To estimate the prediction function based on all available features, we used the 163 observations with complete sequence data; to estimate the prediction function based on the reduced set of features, we used the remaining 163 observations with complete sequence data.
Variable group IC-50
gp120 V2 1
gp120 CD4 binding sites 2
gp120 V3 3
gp41 MPER 4
Region-specific counts of PNG sites 5
Cysteine counts 6
Viral geometry 7

The cross-validated performance, as measured by \(R^2\), of the learner (with tuning parameters selected via cross-validation) and of the learner with each individual value of tuning parameters are shown in Figure 2.2.

Figure 2.2: Cross-validated \(R^2\) for estimated IC-50 (326 observations with complete sequence data)

2.3 Variable importance

2.3.1 Biological importance

We show the population-level variable importance of groups of features (defined in Table 3.1) in predicting IC-50 in Figure 2.4. Importance is defined using the difference in \(R^2\) values.

The plot shows the marginal importance of the group relative to the null model with geographic confounders only.

Figure 2.4: Group variable importance for predicting IC-50. We used the 326 observations with complete sequence data in this analysis. To estimate the prediction functions based on all available features and geographic confounders only, we used 163 observations. To estimate the prediction functions based on the reduced set of features (defined by removing the feature group of interest) and the feature group of interest plus geographic confounders, we used the remaining 163 observations.

We show the population-level variable importance of individual features in predicting IC-50 in Figure 2.5. Importance is defined using the difference in \(R^2\) values.

The plot shows the marginal importance of the feature relative to the null model with geographic confounders only.

Figure 2.5: Individual variable importance for predicting IC-50. We used the 326 observations with complete sequence data in this analysis. To estimate the prediction functions based on all available features and geographic confounders only, we used 163 observations. To estimate the prediction functions based on the reduced set of features (defined by removing the feature of interest) and the feature of interest plus geographic confounders, we used the remaining 163 observations.
